<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-029-071 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 475 087</DOCID><JOURNAL>San Jose Mercury News  Oct 28 1991 p4D(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Archaic patent laws slow software innovation.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Schrage, Michael.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Intellectual property is crucial to economic prosperity andinnovation but a reasonable intellectual property policy does notexist.andP;  The 17-year term for patents is archaic and some legalexperts contend that there is a need for modified patents in thefast-changing software and computer chip worlds.andP;  They alsocontend that the Patent and Trademark Office has confused thesoftware industry by its decision to grant software patents thatare often overly broad.andP;  In turn those who hold these patents areusing them to force firms into paying license fees or intomodifying their software products.andP;  Patents should be spurringinnovation instead of creating complex legal cases.andP;  Policy-makersmust understand that software and biotechnology inventions do notfit into the blanket 17-year patent monopolies that were firstbrought into law in 1790.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     PatentIntellectual PropertyLegal IssuesSoftware PackagesUnited States. Patent and Trademark OfficeCopyright.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>